Cost tools, Cost Explorer, Budgets, and Anomaly Detection. Three tools, three jobs.

Cost Explorer is the interactive analysis console. You slice spend by service, account, region, or tag, over arbitrary time windows. Its Recommendations tab proposes R-Is and Savings Plans based on the last seven, thirty, or sixty days of usage, and its Forecast view projects month-end and next-month spend from the trend. Cost Explorer is where finance and engineering meet, same data, two questions, and importantly it's for analysis, not alerting.

A-W-S Budgets are the proactive alarms. You set a monthly cost budget, a usage budget, like reserved-instance coverage above eighty percent, or a Savings Plans utilisation budget, and Budgets emails you or fires S-N-S when you cross thresholds at fifty, eighty, and a hundred percent, and on forecasted overage. The trick is to budget per team or per workload, not just for the account total, because a one-team overrun is invisible inside a healthy whole-account budget.

Cost Anomaly Detection is the machine-learning layer on top. It learns each service's normal spending pattern and alerts on unexpected spikes. The classic catch is a cryptominer running on a leaked I-A-M key, spinning up G-P-U instances, where the bill spikes hours before anyone notices the breach.

Underneath all three are two enablers: cost allocation tags, which you activate so Cost Explorer and Budgets can slice by team or project, and the A-W-S Cost and Usage Report, the exhaustive line-item export to S3 for deep analysis in Athena or QuickSight. The cue map: to analyse and slice historical spend, Cost Explorer; to alert before crossing a threshold, Budgets; and to catch an unexpected spike, Anomaly Detection.
